name: 'Latin London' Walking Tours
description:
This tour allows participants to experience the city via its Early Modern Latin monuments, inscriptions and poetry, made accessible via modern translations. (c.1500-1700).
It runs from Tower of London to St Paul's Cathedral (c. 2.5 hours).
address: Traitors' Gate, Tower of London, EC3N 4DR

name: 8 Bishopsgate
description: An exciting opportunity to visit the latest contribution to the City of London’s Cluster of tall buildings. The newly completed 8 Bishopsgate by architects WilkinsonEyre is a 50-storey building designed as a series of stacked blocks.

name: AH A Studio
description: This is a newly built and fitted out architecture studio in London Fields. We designed it as a flexible working and event space with the opportunity to align personal wellbeing and professional endeavour in one supportive space.

name: Amazing Women in London Tour
description: Have you ever walked through London and wondered “Where are the statues of women?” or have you ever walked around London and counted the statues of women then tried to do the same with the statues of men?

name: Andaz London Liverpool Street
description:
A concept by Hyatt, Andaz London exuberates history since the 1200's veiled by the new-age decor and a buzzing London neighborhood. 

Step in and explore, as Ryan takes you around for an open house!

name: Bank/Monument station
description: In 2023, Bank/Monument station completed a major upgrade that increased the station's capacity by 40%. Yet while much of the Bank/Monument complex is new, the station dates back over 100 years.  This tour will showcase its history.

name: Battle of Britain Lace Panel: Talk by conservator
description: A new installation of Bromley’s Battle of Britain lace panel is now on display in the Central library and forms part of Bromley Historic Collections. Join us for a talk on the restoration process and specialist textile conservation.

name: Beck Road Studios: Open Studios Exhibitions
description: Explore a vibrant artist community beneath a railway arch at our open studios! Engage with talented artists, discover diverse exhibitions. Join us in celebrating the creativity and sense of togetherness that define this unique space.

name: Burlington House: Society of Antiquaries of London
description: Part of New Burlington House, purpose built in 1875 for London's learned societies. Historic apartments with highlights from the Library and Museum collections on display. Imposing top-lit library with double galleries and marbled columns.

name: C2 Clod Ensemble Studios : Design District
description: The building, designed by Mole Architects, comprises a 2000 square foot rehearsal top-lit studio, open-plan office, music production studio. Constructed entirely from timber, clad in weathered steel and designed to limit energy consumption.
address: C2 Cripps Yard, Soames Walk, Design District, SE10 0BQ

name: Calamity and civility: contrasts in Clerkenwell
description: Tranquil Clerkenwell, so close to the bustling City has a distinct character and intriguing history. Once centred around great religious houses, the area has been the scene of fierce rebellion, innovative architecture, and major commerce.

name: Church of St Mary the Blessed Virgin
description: Founded in 11C, with Jacobean memorial c1615. Burial site of 5 Archbishops of Canterbury.
address: Addington Village Road, Addington, Croydon, CR0 5AS

name: City Information Centre
description: London's main tourist information centre is clad in a specially manufactured system of 220 pre-finished stainless steel panels. The subtly reflective surface provides a striking counterpoint to St Paul's.

name: Clockwise Offices at Bromley Old Town Hall
description: We are a newly opened workspace within the Old Town Hall estate - we've created a workspace that blends modern working with the heritage features of the building.
address: Clockwise, Bromley Old Town Hall, Bromley, BR1 3FE

name: Croydon Archives - Behind the Scenes Tour
description: Join us for a guided tour of Croydon Archives. Go behind the scenes and view our store, which are normally closed to the public, with an opportunity to hear about some of the highlights from the collection from an expert.

name: Crystal Palace Subway – A Conservation Journey
description: A self-guided tour through the active conservation and restoration project revitalising the Crystal Palace Victorian Subway
address: Crystal Palace Parade, Crystal Palace, SE19 2BA

name: Dr Johnson's House
description: Fine example of an early 5-floor Queen Anne town house with original panelling, open staircase and unique 'swinging panels' on the open-plan first floor. Johnson compiled his famous 'Dictionary of the English Language' (1755)  here.

name: Fleet Street Heritage Information Project and Sundial
description: This new sundial faces East so gets only morning sun. It is 10 m. square and was opened in 2021, and is publicly accessible 24/7

name: From Forest to Morris: A walk around Walthamstow
description: A walk around historic Walthamstow showing how this unique area grew from a village into a thriving suburb, its social history and the variety of buildings that can be found where Epping Forest meets William Morris.
address: Outside Costa Coffee at Walthamstow Central Station 5 Station Approac

name: Fruit to Fashion: how a kitchen garden became a world famous piazza
description: The tour charts the evolution of Covent Garden-incorporating the piazza, the wholesale produce market, social residential areas and supporting neighbourhoods - highlighting the social and commercial highs, lows and challenges.

name: Havant House 53
description: A victorian mid terrace house with a dark blue exterior and a zany tiled front garden. Full of original features without being dictated by the era, colour continues inside with a yellow rubber floor in the kitchen.

name: High Elms History tour
description: Discover the fascinating site that was home of John Lubbock and frequently visited by his neighbour Charles Darwin. See remains of the manor house's terraced gardens, stable yard, walled garden and eco-friendly BEECHE education centre.
address: BEECHE Centre High Elms Country Park, Shire Lane, Orpington, BR6 7JH

name: Hornsey Library
description: Hornsey Library is a Grade II listed building, featuring Huxley-Jones' "Reclining figure" sculpture and the intricately etched glass "Hornsey window". A recent refurbishment has added practical updates while keeping the 1960s aesthetic.
address: Hornsey Library, Haringey Park, Haringey, N8 9JA

name: Host of Leyton - Pop-Up Gallery - Dan Lee
description:
Host of Leyton is open 12th - 17th Sept to welcome visitors to see the shop & space and view the work of our special Pop-up exhibition by young artist and landscape designer Dan Lee. 
For more info see @thisishost on Instagram.

name: Hounslow House
description: The London Borough of Hounslow's 2019 contemporary home designed by Sheppard Robson, with iconic iridescent façade and public and private spaces stitched together by a bold and sculptural staircase, is opening up for architectural tours.

name: Lancaster House
description: Commissioned in 1825 by the Duke of York and named York House.  In 1829 the lease was purchased by the first Duke of Sutherland.  In 1913, Lord Leverhulme, bought the lease for the nation and Stafford House became Lancaster House.

name: Leighton House Museum
description: Originally the studio home of Lord Leighton, President of the Royal Academy, the house is one of the most remarkable buildings of 19C. The museum houses an outstanding collection of high Victorian art, including works by Leighton himself.

name: London Living Streets and Footways London
description: A walk to highlight public realm improvements in Camden and the new traffic-free piazza in the Strand. The walk follows a https://footways.london/ route along attractive,low pollution streets, and end with a visit to St Mary le Strand
address: Euston Road, NW1 2AR - near junction with Midland Road, NW1 2AR

name: London Open Form Pavilion of Air
description: A floating roof of sound, GPS-triggered & accessed by headphones & Echoes app to playfully reframe public space as an essential community engagement. One of 15 in an international series drawing on Oskar & Zofia Hansen’s Open Form concept.

name: Lost & Hidden Architecture of South Bank Walk
description: A 2.5 hour walking tour showcasing unexpected and hidden architectural landmarks, both historic and contemporary, of the South Bank area along a route from Lambeth Palace/Garden Museum to Bernie Spain Gardens. Held on 2 weekends.

name: People's Museum Somers Town
description:
A great little museum set in the Grade 2 listed Ossulston Estate - a prime example of pre-war Social housing - based on Karl Marz Hof in Vienna.
Open Wednesdays to Saturdays throughout Festival 
Sunday 11th Event

name: Poroban studio
description: Poroban is a multi-disciplinary design studio, based off Old Kent Road, specialising in low carbon building design. We are offering free design surgeries throughout September and are hosting an open day on Saturday 9th Sept.

name: Present & Correct Stationers
description: Architecture for London designed and built a new home for stationers Present & Correct in a heritage retail unit. In a nod to the neighbouring British Museum, cabinets as 'wunderkammer' display the stationery as objects of desire.

name: Pushkin House
description: The independent cultural centre Pushkin House will contribute to this year's Open House Festival through a programme of events and community initiatives at its Grade-II listed building in Bloomsbury Square.

name: Skip House
description: Skip House is what it says on the tin: a house built in a skip. In protest of London's prohibitively high rental market artist/architect Harrison Marshall has designed and built a house in a skip to live in for a year.

name: St Anne's Church, Limehouse
description: St Anne's Limehouse has been described as 'the finest parish church in England.' Designed by Nicholas Hawksmoor, it is Grade I listed and one of the Major Churches in the Church of England. It is home to a thriving Christian congregation.

name: St Mary's Church Bromley
description:
A plain Victorian Church set in a wooded Churchyard, with a vibrant and striking set of Murals around the altar and the Choir. 
Has indoor toilet facilities. 
A good quality well used organ in good condition, and an excellent accoustic
address: St Mary's Church, College Road, Bromley, BR1 3QG

name: Sun Rain Rooms
description: Set in a Grade II listed Georgian townhouse, Tonkin Liu's studio has been extended. Designed and built by the practice, an innovative timber roof and reflecting pool gathers the bouncing rain, to make it a good place to be on a bad day.

name: The Art House
description: Our 1950's warehouse has been converted to provide a new home for creative studio Acrylicize, to provide a mixture of workshop spaces, co-working and traditional studio space, all centred around a large events and gallery space.

name: The Charterhouse
description: Founded as a Black Death burial ground, the site has served as a Carthusian monastery, Tudor mansion, school and an almshouse, which it remains to this day. The Charterhouse opened to the public in 2017 with a new museum.

name: The City Churches: St Mary-le-Bow
description: Founded by William the Conqueror's Archbishop Lanfranc in 1080 (the significant crypt survives) St Mary-le-Bow was rebuilt, notably by Wren after the Great Fire and by Laurence King in 1964 after WWII destruction. Home of Bow Bells.

name: The City Churches: The Priory Church of St Bartholomew the Great
description: The oldest surviving church in the City of London founded in 1123. Originally part of an Augustinian Priory the church survived the Great Fire and the Blitz.

name: The Gilbert & George Centre
description: The Gilbert & George Centre was originally established as a registered charity by the artist in 2009 with the objective to advance the education of the public in the arts, and generally to advance the arts, architecture, heritage and culture for the benefit of the public.

name: The London Centre
description: Home of NLA, London’s built environment community, and located in the West Wing of the Guildhall complex, the Centre highlights 3 scale architectural models of London: the New London Model, the City Model and the Royal Docks Model.
address: The London Centre, 3 Aldermanbury, City of London, EC2V 7HH

name: The Royal Arsenal - Then, Now and Into the Future
description: The Royal Arsenal was pivotal in every major conflict for over 400 years. After years of being off-limits, many buildings have been re-purposed as performing arts spaces, restaurants, bars and most recently a huge residential complex.
address: Woolwich station of Elizabeth line, Dial Arch Square

name: The Wash Houses
description: RIBA award-winning building.  Part listed frontage with purpose built archive and exhibition building added to the rear in 2002. The building now houses the University's Special Collections & Archives

name: Tower Hamlets Cemetery Park
description: One of the magnificent 7 cemeteries. Burials ceased 1966, now 31 acres of woodland, meadows & ponds including the Soanes Centre (Robson Kelly 1993). Of outstanding importance for flora and fauna, set amongst funereal monuments, some listed
address: Soanes Centre. (On the right the main gates on Southern Grove)

name: Walking around Ermine Street, Spitalfields
description: How can architecture help us to understand a world in flux? We can use buildings as markers of change, seeing the impact of global economic shifts on local streets, the rise and fall of public housing, and the march of 'gentrification'.

name: Walking tour: Sisters in the City
description:
Walking tour: Sisters in the City

A walking tour celebrating the lives of women who’ve made their mark on the City of London over the centuries, from Boudicca to the Suffragettes
address: Kindertransport statue, Hope Square,Liverpool St station, EC2M 7PY

name: Walmer Yard
description: Forming a discreet and private set of four interlocking houses set around an open courtyard, Walmer Yard is Peter Salter's only UK project. The houses now form the home of the Baylight Foundation.

name: Walworth Garden
description: Our timber frame building was designed by Matrix Feminist Design Co-Operative, and built by women. It represents our community's history of activism-the same ethos that transformed our site from dereliction, into a thriving community garden

name: West Wickham Library
description: Art Deco building designed in 1934 by Leslie Kemp and Tasker in International Moderne style. Now the temporary home of West Wickham Library.

name: Yorkton Workshop
description:
Yorkton Workshops is a newly remodeled building that merges Victorian features with modern industrial details.
House to the design firm Pearson Lloyd.
We are thrilled to show you what we do and where we do it.

name: ‘OPEN’ Beyond Beck Road (part II)
description: Architecture and art produced in an unmodified street of 56 houses, railway arch studios, and private galleries between 1974 and 2023. Beck Rd is an iconic artist haven and its residents are key contributors to UK art history.
